[2
Date: 18 June, 1999
From: *Pam Wilson, RVT, Med, CHES*<Pam.Wilson@tdh.state.tx.us>

The borders of the drop-zones for the Oral Rabies Vaccination Program (ORVP)
in South and West-Central Texas have been determined by epidemiologic
surveillance. Vaccine has been distributed on a yearly basis along the
epizootics* outermost boundaries, which were determined by the location of
laboratory-confirmed rabies cases.
In 1995, prior to the first implementation of the ORVP, an emergency
statewide rabies quarantine was enacted. Although it has been modified
through the years, it is still in effect. In essence, Texas Health and
Safety Code, Ch. 826, Rabies Control Act, Rules of the Board of Health
prohibits the transport of coyotes, raccoons, or species of foxes indigenous
to North America from, to, or within the State of Texas except by specified
categories of individuals.
Resources for additional information pertaining to Texas* ORVP include:
Texas Department of Health*s Zoonosis Control Division web site:
http://www.tdh.state.tx.us/zoonosis
Fearneyhough MG, Wilson PJ, Clark KA et al. Results of an oral rabies
vaccination program for coyotes. J Am Vet Med Assoc 1998;212:498-502
Meehan SK. Rabies epizootic in coyotes combated with oral vaccination
program. J Am Vet Med Assoc 1995;206:1097-1099
---
Pam Wilson, RVT, MEd, CHES
Texas Department of Health, Zoonosis Control Division
e-mail: Pam.Wilson@tdh.state.tx.us
